---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'Marketplace &amp; e-commerce app development';
const description =
  'Native iOS and Android apps for marketplaces and online retail. Buyer + seller flows, payments, listings, search, push, and store submission — end-to-end by Apriori Studio.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="Marketplace mobile app development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/apps', label: 'Mobile apps' },
    { href: '/apps/marketplace', label: 'Marketplace &amp; e-commerce apps' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Marketplace and shopping apps are some of the most-used categories on every phone — and
    also some of the hardest to get right. They live or die by the quality of small details:
    how fast a product image loads on a slow connection, how few taps it takes to buy
    something seen yesterday, how clearly notifications surface a sale without becoming spam.
    We build marketplace apps with those small things treated as the main thing.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    Branded retail apps for an existing online store (so your customers can re-order with one
    tap and get push notifications about restocks). Vertical marketplaces (handmade, vintage,
    refurbished electronics, niche gear). Two-sided platforms with separate buyer and seller
    apps. Live-shopping experiences with video and chat. Subscription-box style
    "discover-then-buy" apps. The patterns differ by category, but the underlying engineering
    challenges are similar.
  </p>

  <h2>End-to-end work</h2>

  <h3>Discovery and information architecture</h3>
  <p>
    We start by mapping the journeys: how a buyer discovers something, considers it, buys it,
    receives it, returns it. For two-sided apps we map the seller's journey too: listing,
    pricing, fulfilment, payouts, support. The information architecture follows from those
    journeys — categories, filters, search, recommendations, account areas. We avoid copying
    Amazon's structure unless that's actually what your customers expect.
  </p>

  <h3>Native or cross-platform?</h3>
  <p>
    For most retail apps, <strong>React Native</strong> with shared business logic and
    platform-specific UI flourishes is the right balance. For apps with heavy media (live
    video, AR try-on, virtual rooms) we go fully native with Swift and Kotlin. Either way the
    backend is shared and the apps share a single design system rather than diverging.
  </p>

  <h3>Catalogue, search and filters</h3>
  <p>
    A small catalogue (under a few hundred SKUs) can use the backend's built-in search. Past
    that, we plug in proper search (Algolia, Meilisearch, Manticore) with typo tolerance,
    synonyms, faceted filtering, and instant results as the user types. We add infinite scroll
    that doesn't memory-leak, image placeholders so layouts don't jump, and offline caching of
    recently viewed items so the app stays useful on a poor connection.
  </p>

  <h3>Product detail pages that convert</h3>
  <p>
    Image gallery with pinch-to-zoom and lazy loading. Variants (size, colour, configuration)
    that update price and availability in real time. Reviews and ratings. Cross-sell modules
    where they make sense. Sticky add-to-cart on long pages. Apple Pay and Google Pay buttons
    that work in one tap. Stock and shipping info above the fold. Shareable deep links so a
    user can send a product to a friend and have it open in the app, not the browser.
  </p>

  <h3>Cart, checkout and payments</h3>
  <p>
    A persistent cart that survives app close. Checkout in as few steps as possible —
    sometimes a single page, sometimes split if it improves trust. Apple Pay and Google Pay
    front and centre (one-tap purchase from a saved card). Stripe for card payments, with 3D
    Secure handled correctly. Klarna or Clearpay for buy-now-pay-later. Address autocomplete
    (Google Places or Loqate) so a returning customer doesn't have to type. Tax calculation
    based on shipping address and product type.
  </p>

  <h3>Two-sided marketplaces</h3>
  <p>
    For platforms with sellers as well as buyers, we build either two separate apps or a
    single app with a seller-mode toggle. Listing flow with image upload (with on-device
    compression and a fallback to upload via Wi-Fi if connection is poor). Inventory and
    order management. Stripe Connect for split payments and seller payouts. Messaging between
    buyers and sellers with typing indicators and offline queueing. Dispute resolution flows
    that don't require us to write a custom support panel from scratch.
  </p>

  <h3>Push notifications</h3>
  <p>
    Order updates (placed, shipped, delivered). Price drops on saved items. Restock alerts.
    Personalised picks at a sensible cadence (not three a day). Cart abandonment if the user
    opted in. Each category goes through the right notification permission group so users can
    turn off "marketing" without losing "order updates." We design these as a system, not as
    one-off broadcasts.
  </p>

  <h3>Account, orders and re-engagement</h3>
  <p>
    Order history with reorder buttons. Saved addresses and payment methods. Returns initiated
    in-app. Wishlists. Loyalty points or rewards if you have them. Sign-in with Apple, Google,
    or email — required by Apple if you offer any third-party login. Account deletion in-app
    (Apple now requires this for any app that lets you create an account).
  </p>

  <h3>Analytics and growth</h3>
  <p>
    Conversion funnel tracking from view → add-to-cart → checkout → purchase, segmented by
    source. Cohort retention. Re-engagement campaigns triggered by inactivity. App Store and
    Play Store optimisation (keywords, screenshots, video preview). We integrate the analytics
    you'll actually use, not all of them — too many SDKs slow the app and confuse the data.
  </p>

  <h3>App Store and Google Play submission</h3>
  <p>
    Marketplace apps draw extra scrutiny from Apple's reviewers (commerce policy, in-app
    purchase rules, refund handling, age ratings if you sell anything age-restricted). We
    prepare the submission with the right metadata, privacy declarations, and screenshots,
    and we respond to reviewer questions in your name. Google Play's process is more
    automated but trips on permissions and policy items — we handle those too.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A branded retail app for an existing store (catalogue sync, account, cart, checkout, push)
    typically lands at £20,000 to £35,000 for both platforms. A two-sided marketplace with
    seller apps and Stripe Connect starts around £40,000 and is quoted per project. Backend
    hosting, payment processor fees, and any SaaS subscriptions (push, analytics, search) are
    billed to you directly.
  </p>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>
    A retail app first version typically ships in twelve to sixteen weeks. A two-sided
    marketplace MVP is twenty to twenty-eight weeks, depending on the scope of seller tools.
    Either way, we ship to TestFlight and Play Console internal track every fortnight so you
    can use the app on your own phone throughout.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
